@@eThe Saltglass Reach@@N

  The jurisdictional transition corridor from inland desert to the
eastern sea. Where the @@ycaravan law@@N of the oasis-pyramid civilization
meets the @@lmaritime risk law@@N of the coast, neither system yielding
cleanly to the other.

  Four bands define the crossing. The @@WMirror Flats@@N are hard salt
crust -- remnants of the vanished Iseth Reach's terminal evaporation
basin -- that blind by day and reflect moonlight at night. Caravans
cross at dawn and dusk when the reflection angle is survivable. The
@@eGlasswind Belts@@N are fields of wind-cut silica shards formed when the
Ninth Meridian catastrophe's thermal pulse fused desert sand into
brittle sheets. Experienced guides read glass color to navigate: milky
shards mean stable ground, amber warns of thermal faults, violet means
turn back. The @@yTariff Cairn Lines@@N are ruined checkpoint chains --
three parallel routes once certifying cargo for the swift, heavy, and
sealed trades. The @@gTidemouth Dunes@@N mark the brackish approach to the
coast, where the first crab burrows signal half a day to Mafdet.

  The Reach's defining innovation was the @@yShoreward Conversion@@N -- the
formal process by which cargo, contracts, and obligations were
translated from inland desert law to maritime contract law. At the
@@eShoreward Seal@@N, a basalt slab carved with both charter notation and
loading symbols, water-debt was discharged by a symbolic pouring, cargo
owners spoke a formulaic oath transferring liability from road to sea,
and relic consignments were reclassified from theological provenance
to practical hazard categories.

  @@eReach Wardens@@N patrol the surviving cairn lines, issuing transit seals
accepted with varying trust at both inland courts and coastal harbors.
@@rRed Sand Outriders@@N -- agents of Mafdet's debt-leverage consortium --
operate inland to acquire distressed cargo at exploitative rates.
@@yGlasswalk Guides@@N know the safe routes through the Glasswind Belts,
their families passing down route songs that encode distance, direction,
and hazard in rhythmic chant older than written language.

  The Reach is not empty desert. It is a @@yjurisdictional gradient@@N
between two legal civilizations, where every cairn, marker, and path
implies a former purpose -- toll collection, cargo certification,
jurisdictional boundary -- and where the glass and salt terrain is
evidence of catastrophe, not random hazard.
